  "en_notes_yusuf": [
    {
      "note_no": "1779",
      "note": "Certainly metaphorically: probably also literally. By Eastern custom the place of honour at a ceremonial reception is on a seat on a dais, with a special cushion of honour, such as is assigned to a bridegroom at his reception. To show his high respect for his parents, Joseph made them sit on a throne of dignity. On the other hand, his parents and his brothers?all performed the ceremony of prostration before Joseph in recognition of his supreme rank in Egypt under the Pharaoh, And thus was fulfilled the dream or vision of his youth (12:4 above, and n. 1633)."
    },
    {
      "note_no": "1780",
      "note": "Note how modest Joseph is throughout. The first things he thinks of among Allah's gracious favours to him are: (1) that he was brought uot of prison and publicly proclaimed to be honest and virtuous; and (2) that his dear father was restored to him, as well as the brothers who had persecuted him all his life. He will say nothing against them personally. In his husn zann (habit of interpreting everyone and everything in the most favourable and charitable light), he looks upon them as having been misled. It was Satan (the power of Evil) that set them against him. But now all is rectified by the grace of Allah, to Whom he renders due praise.<br/>Latif: see n. 2844 to 22:63; the fourth meaning mentioned there applies here, with echoes of the other meanings."
    }
